					<head>Abraham's Pentateuch and Rashi</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79066420" rend="visible">
						<summary>Pentateuch with Rashi's commentary and Targum Onḳelos; the Five Scrolls; the Hafṭarot; Job with Rashi's commentary and Megilat Antiochus. Aka 'Abraham's Pentateuch and Rashi'.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="tmr-Hebr">Hebrew, Aramaic</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79066420">
							<locus from="1v" to="311v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Torah ʿim perush Rash"i, megilot ṿe-hafṭarot</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">תורה עם פרוש רש"י, מגילות  והפטרות </title>
							<author>
								<persName xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/19684048">Shelomoh Yitsḥaḳi Rash"i</persName>
							</author>
							<decoNote type="initial">14 decorated initial words in brown ink and red.<locus n="4v, 9v, 14v, 24r, 31v, 54r, 57v, 132v, 220r, 223v, 231r, 239r, 271r, 298r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="initial">Decorated parashah sign.<locus n="123r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="paratext">2 micrographic designs.<locus n="177r, 177v"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="initial">2 unfinished initial words.<locus n="220r, 289r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<listBibl>
								<bibl>
									<ref target="Wright_1972" type="page">246, 459</ref>
								</bibl>
								<bibl>
									<ref target="Kogman_Narkiss_2009" type="page">319-351</ref>
								</bibl>
							</listBibl>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="1v" to="3r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">A list of Psalms </title>
							<note>
								<p>Enlists those Psalms which are liturgically connected with the weekly pericopes and the services of the fests and fasts.</p>
							</note>
							<incipit xml:lang="he">לוח המזמורים...מכל השנה.<locus n="1v"/>
							</incipit>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="4v" to="57v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Genesis </title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="57v" to="101r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Exodus</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="101r" to="132v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Leviticus</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="132v" to="178r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Numbers</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="178r" to="219r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Deuteronomy</title>
							<explicit xml:lang="he">חזק ונתחזק הסופר לא יזק לא היום ולא לעולם עד שיעלה חמור בסולם אשר יעקב אבינו חלם.<locus n="219r"/>
							</explicit>
							<note>
								<p>The final formula is repated also for the Targum and commentary.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="220r" to="223v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Song of Songs</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="223v" to="226r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Ruth</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="226r" to="231r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Lamentations</title>
							<note>
								<p>Folio 230r: a later addition of Ps. 137 and a scribal subscription, giving an acrostych of the name Yaʿaḳov.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="231r" to="239r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Ecclesiastes</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="239r" to="244v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Esther</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="245r" to="288v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Hafṭarot for the whole year.</title>
							<note>
								<p>The first two Hafṭarot are accompanied by Rashi's commentary, but only the Hafṭarot  for Pesaḥ and Shavuʿot  have the Targum. </p>
								<p>The sribe's name appears on folio 288r as <name type="person" role="scribe">Abraham</name>.</p>
							</note>
							<quote xml:lang="he">וזה תרגום של הפטרה אמיר דאיתמר בנבואה על ידי יהושע נבייא כמה דפריש יהונתן בר עוזיאל וכדו הוה פריש אמיר. <locus n="282v"/>
							</quote>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="289r" to="308v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Job</title>
							<note>
								<p>Accompanied by Rashi's commentary.</p>
								<p>Folio 307v contains 2Chron. 24:5, 1Kings 8:27, Gen. 19:16, punctuated and accentuated.</p>
								<p>Folio 308r contains the benedictions that are said before and after the reading of Hafṭarot.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="309r" to="309v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Megilat Antiochus</title>
							<note>
								<p>In Hebrew, with vowel-points.</p>
							</note>
							<explicit xml:lang="he">תם ונשלם " האל הנותן מאורות בעולם " יאיר עינינו אור עולם " ותחיש הישועה בעולם " לעם חכו לך מעולם "<locus n="309v"/>
							</explicit>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Vellum codex, Ashkenazi square and semi-cursive script, partially punctuated.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">311 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>265</height>
										<width>210</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>185/140</height>
										<width>150/85</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>311 folios (+ 2 modern unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning, and 2 older and 2 modern unfoliated paper flyleaves at the end); folios 1-3 are older paper flyleaves</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>39 quires: i-xxi8 (folios 4-171), xxii6 (folios 172-177), xxiii-xxvi8 (folios 178-209), xxvii10 (folios 210-219), xxviii-xxix8 (folios 220-235), xxx6 (folios 236-241), xxxi-xxxv8 (folios 242-281), xxxvi6 (folios 282-287), xxxvii10-1 (folios 288-296), xxxviii8 (folios 297-304), xxxix8-1 (folios 305-311). </p>
									<p>No catchwords.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 2" ruledLines="23 30" writtenLines="22 29">
									<p>Watermarks on <locus n="2r"/>, and on <locus n="fse001r"/>. The first watermark is a hand, the second watermark is a vase with a crescent at the top and a monogramm (CO?), similar to <ref target="Heawood_1950" type="number">3603</ref> (dated to 1646, England).</p>
									<p>Single leaves were written by another scribe; their codicological elements being different from those by the original scribe. At the bottom of these pages, one can discern the scribe's attempts to enlarge the letters in order to fit the text into the remaining empty spaces. These leaves were glued into the margins of now-missing pages which were torn out from the original Pentateuch.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="2">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square and semi-cursive script, partially punctuated.		<name type="person" role="scribe">Avraham ben Yitsḥaḳ</name>: inscribed with his name in two colophons and an additional scribal formula: 'Grow stronger and let us grow stronger. May no harm befall on Abraham [ben ha-ḳadosh rabi Yitsḥaḳ] the copyist not today and not ever until the donkey ascends the ladder to the heavens about which our father Yaʿaḳov had dreamed' [English translation], 14th century (219r, 288r, 307r); the name Avram and Avraham is decorated several times, (e.g. 14r, 21r, 141v, 186r, 307r). <name type="person" role="scribe">Yaʿaḳov</name>: inscribed with his name on folio 230r: may the owner of the book have eternal life for volunteering to write the missing pages.  It appears that Yaʿaḳov acquired the Pentateuch with a few of its pages missing and he himself filled in the missing gaps.
							</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Ḥayim bar Yaʿaḳov Raʿagi: inscribed with his name (folios 307v, 311r, 311v); acrostic of Yaʿaḳov, 15th century (folio 230r).
							</p>
							<p>Meʾir bar Meʾir : inscribed with his name, 15th century (folios 307v, 311v).
							</p>
							<p>Shemuʾel bar Meʾir : inscribed with his name, 15th century (folio 310v); acquisition note by the same hand (folio 311r ).
							</p>
							<p>Meʾir Shemuʾel: inscribed with his name, 15th century (folio 4r).
							</p>
							<p>Meʾir: inscription in Hebrew: 'I am Meʾir', 15th century (folio 308v).
							</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name> (b. 1672, d. 1726), Old English scholar and librarian: inscribed with his name: '<q>Liber Humfredi Wanley</q>' (folio 1r ) (<ref target="Wright_1972"/>).
							</p>
							<p>Illegible Hebrew inscriptions (folio 4r). </p>
							<p>On the inner sides of the cover there is a leaf pasted in, belonging to what appears to have been a Latin Law Dictionary of c16th century.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Black leather with the Harley arms in the centre.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
